{"id":22,"date":"2020-08-02T10:45:46","date_gmt":"2020-08-02T10:45:46","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/karenhilltribes\/?page_id=22"},"modified":"2020-09-23T11:15:46","modified_gmt":"2020-09-23T11:15:46","slug":"culture","status":"publish","type":"page","link":"https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/the-karen-people\/culture\/","title":{"rendered":"Culture"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<section id=\"page-section-block_5f69dc6961a89\" \nclass=\"page-section page-section--transparent\">\n    <div class=\"container\">\n        <div class=\"page-section__wrapper \">\n            <div class=\"page-section__image\" style=\"max-height:400px\">\n                <img src=\"https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/spirithouse-2.jpg\" alt=\"Karen culture in Northern Thailand!\" \/>\n            <\/div>\n            <div class=\"page-section__content\">\n                <h2 class=\"page-section__title\">Karen culture in Northern Thailand!<\/h2>\n                                <p class=\"page-section__body no-margin-xs\"><p>The Karen people live in Burma and Northern Thailand, and the groups we work with live in small villages dotted across the remote mountains in Mai Hong Son.<\/p>\n<p>Whilst Thailand is predominantly a Buddhist country, the Karen are Animist, Buddhist and 30% Christian. Religion is central to many aspects of identity and culture: moral and cultural values are passed down through stories and songs. In Animist villages the witch doctor plays an important role.<\/p>\n<\/p>                                            <\/div>\n        <\/div>\n    <\/div>\n<\/section>\n\n\n<section id=\"page-section-block_5f69dd1c61a8a\" \nclass=\"page-section page-section--cream\">\n    <div class=\"container\">\n        <div class=\"page-section__wrapper page-section--align-right\">\n            <div class=\"page-section__image\" style=\"max-height:400px\">\n                <img src=\"https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/KHT-Village-Life-Small-0158.jpg\" alt=\"Clothing\" \/>\n            <\/div>\n            <div class=\"page-section__content\">\n                <h2 class=\"page-section__title\">Clothing<\/h2>\n                                <p class=\"page-section__body no-margin-xs\"><p>The Karen make their own costumes and shoulder bags which are hand woven by the women sitting on the ground using a traditional strap loom. Patterns are handed down from generation to generation.<\/p>\n<p>Some natural dyes are used, produced from tree and plant extracts, and artificial dyes are also used to create the brighter colours. Weaving is a skill that remains important to the culture. They also commonly carry cotton shoulder bags, also woven in the villages.<\/p>\n<\/p>                                            <\/div>\n        <\/div>\n    <\/div>\n<\/section>\n\n\n<section id=\"page-section-block_5f69dd3f61a8b\" \nclass=\"page-section page-section--transparent\">\n    <div class=\"container\">\n        <div class=\"page-section__wrapper \">\n            <div class=\"page-section__image\" style=\"max-height:400px\">\n                <img src=\"https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/women3.jpg\" alt=\"Food\" \/>\n            <\/div>\n            <div class=\"page-section__content\">\n                <h2 class=\"page-section__title\">Food<\/h2>\n                                <p class=\"page-section__body no-margin-xs\"><p>The traditional Karen diet is made up largely of different rice dishes. That is why rice is of outmost importance for families to grow!<\/p>\n<p>Almost every farming family grow chili, garlic and coriander, as these are importance spices for the dishes.<\/p>\n<p>The Karen also keep chickens and pigs, as well as occasionally go fishing in the rivers.<\/p>\n<p>Many families also grow papaya, banana and mangoes.<\/p>\n<\/p>                                            <\/div>\n        <\/div>\n    <\/div>\n<\/section>\n\n\n\n<aside class=\"cta cta--transparent\" id=